    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioTacc"/>, <citedRange>X.43, XII.92</citedRange></bibl>, whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>94</citedRange>, and fig. 73</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>097050</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#beschi1970"/>, p. <citedRange>204</citedRange> (date of base)</bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#santucci2003"/>, p. <citedRange>199</citedRange></bibl> (history of the tomb);
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.2</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#ensoli2022"/></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                            <ab>
                                <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-66126"><name nymRef="#Φράσων">Φράσων</name> 
                                <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65271"><name nymRef="#Παρμενίων" type="patronymic">Παρμενίωνος</name></persName></persName>
                          </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                 <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phrason fils de Parmenion.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phrason son of Parmenion.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phrason figlio di Parmenion.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The date based on the lettering is not contradictory with some of the funerary material found inside the underground chamber of the rectangular tomb which anteceded 
                    the prestigious tomb N 1 (so-called Windmill Tomb) and might belong to that first stage. <bibl><ptr target="#ensoli2022"/></bibl> insisting on that point, dissociates the inscribed base and 
                     circular tomb which, in her view, was that of a wealthy person, namely king Magas.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
